'''Islay Conolly''', [[MBE]] (born 1923) is a [[Culture of the Cayman Islands|Caymanian]] teacher and school administrator. Serving as a teacher and principal at various schools on the islands, she became Chief Education Officer in 1970. She has been honored by the Caymanian government with the Spirit of Excellence Award during National Heroes Day and was first recipient of the Chamber of Commerce's  Lifetime Achievement Award in Education. Conolly was honored as a member of the [[Order of the British Empire]] in 1981.

==Early life==
Islay Leonie Bodden was born in 1923 on [[Cayman Brac]] in the [[Cayman Islands]] [[Colony of Jamaica]], which at the time was part of the [[British Empire]] to Ella and Harris Bodden.{{sfn|Jamaican Marriage Records|1950|p=2932}}{{sfn|''Personalities Caribbean''|1983|p=158}}{{sfn|''Cayman Compass''|2016}}

==Career==
After completing her schooling, Bodden began her career in education as the headmistress of the Creek School in Cayman Brac in 1947.{{sfn|Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce|2008}} On 28 December 1950, in Kingston, Jamaica, she married Callan Hunter Ritch{{sfn|Jamaican Marriage Records|1950|p=2932}} and they would subsequently have a son, David and separate.{{sfn|''Cayman Compass''|2008}} Ritch moved to [[Grand Cayman]] and worked as the principal of East End Primary School.{{sfn|Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce|2008}}{{sfn|''Cayman Compass''|2016}} On 12 April 1958, she married [[William Warren Conolly]],{{sfn|''Personalities Caribbean''|1983|p=158}} and the couple would later have two children, a son Burns and a daughter Jackie.{{sfn|''Cayman Compass''|2008}}

In 1970 Conolly was appointed as the Cayman's Chief Education Officer. Among innovations she brought to the school system were public [[deaf education|education for the deaf]] and a junior college system.{{sfn|Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce|2008}} Prior to her tenure, the only available schooling for deaf students was private education and there was no universal standard or public education for deaf students.{{sfn|Lucas|1990|p=261}}{{sfn|Paxton|1981|p=328}} In 1981, Conolly was honored as a member of the [[Order of the British Empire]]{{sfn|''The London Gazette''|1981|p=18}} and she retired in 1982.{{sfn|Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce|2008}} In 2008, she was honored by the Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce as the inaugural recipient of their Lifetime Achievement Award in Education.{{sfn|Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce|2008}} The following year, she was honored by the Caymanian government during the [[Heroes' Day#Heroes' Day in the Cayman Islands|National Heroes Day Celebrations]] with a Spirit of Excellence Award.{{sfn|''Cayman Compass''|2009}}

