'''Jessie Lillian Furze''' (4 February 1903 – 5 November 1984) was an [[England|English]] composer and pianist. She was born in [[Wallington, London|Wallington]], [[Surrey]], and studied at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] where she won the Cuthbert Nunn prize for composition. After completing her studies she worked as a music teacher. She married Willem L.F. Nijhof and died in Croydon.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA179&dq=Jessie+Furze+(1903%E2%80%931984)&hl=en&ei=YTcETYGkJYP-8Aaj1JDnAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Jessie%20Furze%20(1903%E2%80%931984)&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=International who's who in music and musicians' directory: Volume 10|author=Kay, Ernest|year=1985}}</ref>
==Works== Furze composed over 250 works, mostly didactic music. She also published songbooks with collections of songs. Selected compositions include: *''I had a dove'' (Text: John Keats) *''Robin Redbreast'' *''The Drummer Boy'' *''Cheerful Sparrows'' *''Falling Leaves'' *''The Broken Doll'' published by The Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music in 1926. *''Molly-O'' *''Grandmother's Story'' *''The Truants'' *''All Alone: Two's Company'' *''Farwell Mari'' *''Merrymakers ''published by The Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music in 1927.
