'''''The Price of Admission: How America's Ruling Class Buys Its Way into Elite Colleges - and Who Gets Left Outside the Gates''''' is a 2005 book by [[Daniel Golden]], a recipient of the [[Pulitzer Prize]] in journalism. The book criticizes admissions at elite American universities, including preferences given to the wealthy, children of celebrities, and [[Legacy preferences|legacy]] applicants. It also documents discrimination against [[Asian Americans]] in the admissions process.

In 2017, the book was referenced by [[John Oliver]], in the [[late-night talk show]] ''[[Last Week Tonight]]'', regarding the way [[Jared Kushner]] got admitted to [[Harvard University]], soon after the private [[Ivy League]] [[research university]] received a donation from Kushner's [[Charles Kushner|father]].<ref name="Last Week Tonight">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wD8AwgO0AQI "Ivanka & Jared"]. [[Last Week Tonight]]. Season 4 Episode 10. Minute 14:10. Retrieved April 23, 2017.</ref> At the end of 2016 Golden unfold the chain of events himself, expressing "gratitude to Jared Kushner", for "reviving interest the book".{{refn|{{cite news|title=How did ‘less than stellar’ high school student Jared Kushner get into Harvard? |first=Daniel | last=Golden |date=November 18, 2016|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/18/jared-kushner-harvard-donald-trump-son-in-law}} }}

Then [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] Dean of Admissions [[Marilee Jones]] is quoted in ''The Price of Admission'' as describing a [[Korean-American]] student as “yet another textureless math grind.”<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/148996763|title=The price of admission : how America's ruling class buys its way into elite colleges--and who gets left outside the gates|last=1957-|first=Golden, Daniel,|date=2007|publisher=Three Rivers Press|isbn=9781400097975|edition= 1st paperback |location=New York|oclc=148996763}}</ref> Two years after the book's publication, Jones was found out to have fabricated several degrees in order get her first job at the MIT Admission Office.

